  "text": "During the experiments, the thermos for DNA denaturation can maintain its temperature between 98 and 93°C. At this temperature range, DNA can be rapidly denatured. Melting curve analyses of PCR amplicons have demonstrated that most DNA or PCR amplicons melt/ denature completely at 90°C and below [CITATION_1] , therefore, the slight temperature drop throughout the duration of the PCR reaction will not prohibit denaturation and the subsequent annealing of primers to the denatured DNA.",
